  "text": "Pod security context validation in Kubernetes v1.32.0 is implemented across three layers: API-level admission validation, Pod Security Admission (PSA) policy checks, and kubelet runtime enforcement.\n\n## 1. runAsNonRoot Enforcement\n\n**API validation** (`pkg/apis/core/validation/validation.go`): The `ValidateSecurityContext` function validates the container-level `SecurityContext`, including `runAsUser` (must be a valid UID). The `validatePodSpecSecurityContext` function validates the pod-level `PodSecurityContext`, including `runAsUser` and `runAsGroup`. Neither function directly rejects `runAsNonRoot=false` at admission — that is left to PSA.\n\n**PSA policy** (`staging/src/k8s.io/pod-security-admission/policy/check_runAsNonRoot.go`): `CheckRunAsNonRoot()` registers a Restricted-level check. The implementation `runAsNonRoot_1_0()` inspects `podSpec.SecurityContext.RunAsNonRoot` and each container's `SecurityContext.RunAsNonRoot`. It rejects pods where any container explicitly sets `runAsNonRoot=false`, or where neither the pod nor the container sets `runAsNonRoot=true`.\n\n**Kubelet runtime** (`pkg/kubelet/kuberuntime/security_context_others.go` for Linux, `pkg/kubelet/kuberuntime/security_context_windows.go` for Windows): `verifyRunAsNonRoot()` is called at container start time (from `kuberuntime_container.go`). It uses `securitycontext.DetermineEffectiveSecurityContext()` (in `pkg/securitycontext/util.go`) to merge pod and container security contexts, then checks if the effective `RunAsNonRoot=true` and the container would run as UID 0.\n\n## 2. Privileged Container Check\n\n**API validation** (`pkg/apis/core/validation/validation.go`): `ValidateSecurityContext()` checks `sc.Privileged` against the cluster-level `capabilities.Get().AllowPrivileged` flag. If the cluster disallows privileged containers, setting `privileged=true` is rejected with a Forbidden error.\n\n**PSA policy** (`staging/src/k8s.io/pod-security-admission/policy/check_privileged.go`): `CheckPrivileged()` registers a Baseline-level check. `privileged_1_0()` iterates all containers and rejects any pod where a container sets `securityContext.privileged=true`.\n\n**Kubelet runtime** (`pkg/kubelet/container/helpers.go`): `HasPrivilegedContainer()` checks if any container in the pod has `Privileged=true`. This is used in `pkg/kubelet/kuberuntime/kuberuntime_sandbox.go` to set the sandbox's `LinuxSandboxSecurityContext.Privileged` flag. The `determineEffectiveSecurityContext()` in `pkg/kubelet/kuberuntime/security_context.go` also propagates the `Privileged` field to the runtime container security context via `convertToRuntimeCapabilities`.\n\n## 3. Capabilities Validation\n\n**API validation** (`pkg/apis/core/validation/validation.go`): `ValidateSecurityContext()` checks that if `allowPrivilegeEscalation=false`, the container cannot add `CAP_SYS_ADMIN` to its capabilities. This is the only capabilities check at the API validation layer.\n\n**PSA policy — Baseline** (`staging/src/k8s.io/pod-security-admission/policy/check_capabilities_baseline.go`): `CheckCapabilitiesBaseline()` registers a Baseline-level check. `capabilitiesBaseline_1_0()` iterates all containers and rejects any that add capabilities beyond the default allowed set (AUDIT_WRITE, CHOWN, DAC_OVERRIDE, FOWNER, FSETID, KILL, MKNOD, NET_BIND_SERVICE, SETFCAP, SETGID, SETPCAP, SETUID, SYS_CHROOT).\n\n**PSA policy — Restricted** (`staging/src/k8s.io/pod-security-admission/policy/check_capabilities_restricted.go`): `CheckCapabilitiesRestricted()` registers a Restricted-level check (overriding the baseline check). `capabilitiesRestricted_1_22()` requires all containers to drop ALL capabilities and allows only NET_BIND_SERVICE to be added. `capabilitiesRestricted_1_25()` adds a Windows OS exemption.\n\n**Kubelet runtime** (`pkg/kubelet/kuberuntime/security_context.go`): `convertToRuntimeCapabilities()` converts the `v1.Capabilities` struct to the CRI runtime API `Capability` struct, which is then applied to the container via `determineEffectiveSecurityContext()`.\n\n## 4. seccompProfile Enforcement\n\n**API validation** (`pkg/apis/core/validation/validation.go`): Multiple functions handle seccomp validation:\n- `validateSeccompProfileField()` validates the `SeccompProfile` struct (type must be valid, `localhostProfile` required when type is Localhost)\n- `validateSeccompProfileType()` validates the `SeccompProfileType` enum value\n- `ValidateSeccompProfile()` validates the legacy annotation-based seccomp profile string\n- `ValidateSeccompPodAnnotations()` validates seccomp annotations on pods\n- `validateSeccompAnnotationsAndFields()` and `validateSeccompAnnotationsAndFieldsMatch()` ensure that when both annotation and field are set, they agree\n- `validatePodSpecSecurityContext()` calls `validateSeccompProfileField()` for the pod-level seccomp profile\n- `ValidateSecurityContext()` calls `validateSeccompProfileField()` for the container-level seccomp profile\n\n**PSA policy — Baseline** (`staging/src/k8s.io/pod-security-admission/policy/check_seccompProfile_baseline.go`): `CheckSeccompBaseline()` registers a Baseline-level check. `seccompProfileBaseline_1_0()` validates legacy seccomp annotations (v1.0-v1.18). `seccompProfileBaseline_1_19()` validates the `seccompProfile` field, rejecting any profile type other than RuntimeDefault or Localhost.\n\n**PSA policy — Restricted** (`staging/src/k8s.io/pod-security-admission/policy/check_seccompProfile_restricted.go`): `CheckSeccompProfileRestricted()` registers a Restricted-level check. `seccompProfileRestricted_1_19()` requires that every pod or container explicitly sets a valid seccomp profile (RuntimeDefault or Localhost) — unlike the baseline check, it also rejects pods where no profile is set at all. `seccompProfileRestricted_1_25()` adds a Windows OS exemption.\n\n**Kubelet runtime** (`pkg/kubelet/kuberuntime/helpers.go`): `fieldSeccompProfile()` converts a `v1.SeccompProfile` to the CRI `SecurityProfile`. `getSeccompProfile()` resolves the effective seccomp profile for a container by checking container-level first, then pod-level, then falling back to RuntimeDefault if `seccompDefault` is enabled. These are called from `security_context.go`'s `determineEffectiveSecurityContext()` which applies the seccomp profile to the container at runtime."
